text.label: Text
text.value: The painting represents Russia as a two-headed eagle who attacks the Finnish Maiden, trying to rob her book of laws. The painting became famous for its representation of the resistance of the Finnish people.

text.label: Text
text.value: During the late 1800s and early 1900s, the "golden age" of Finnish art and national romanticism emerged. This period held special significance due to Finland's historical context: it was part of the Russian Empire from 1809 to 1917 as the Grand Duchy of Finland. The Finnish identity and national spirit gradually reinforced under Russian rule, leading to the establishment of the independent Republic of Finland.Â

title.label: Title
title.value: The birth of Lake Tuusula artist community

text.label: Text
text.value: At the turn of the 20th century, a unique artist community was born on the shores of Lake Tuusula and it was in many ways very significant to Finland and Finnish culture. The peaceful surroundings combined with affordable housing costs and excellent transport connections to Helsinki attracted several artists, writers, and composers to move into the area: Jean Sibelius (1865-1957), Juhani Aho (1861-1921), Eero JÃ¤rnefelt (1863-1937), Pekka Halonen (1865-1935), J. H. Erkko (1849â€“1906) and many others. Also Finnish national writer Aleksis Kivi (1834-1872) lived the last few months of his life in the area. All of the artists belonged to the same circle of friends and fuelled one anotherâ€™s creativity. They were amongst the key persons to evolve the Finnish artistic scene and shared a desire to get as close to the nature and the "real" Finnishness as possible. However, the residents also led a very international life: most of them studied abroad and followed European art trends.

text.label: Text
text.value: Juhani Aho, originally Johannes Brofeldt, was the first Finnish author who made a living by writing. He started as a realist but moved towards neoromanticism later during his career. His first novel Rautatie (â€œRailwayâ€) was published in 1884 and it is considered as one of the Finnish literature classics. He was also involved in founding the PÃ¤ivÃ¤lehti newspaper, the predecessor of â€œHelsingin Sanomatâ€, the biggest newspaper in Finland today.

title.label: Title
title.value: Portrait of Juhani Aho (1891) painted by his wife Venny Soldan-Brofeldt

text.label: Text
text.value: Pekka Halonen was one of the masters of the Golden Age in Finnish Art. He was born in the countryside but moved to Helsinki to study at the Finnish Art Societyâ€™s Art School. Later on, he had the chance to continue his studies in Paris and to familiarise himself with the European metropolises as well. He was inspired by the Roman art and Renaissance frescoes, but ended up depicting his homeland in his work, becoming a representative of national romanticism and Karelianism.

text.label: Text
text.value:
The double portrait, the artist and his wife, was a rare subject in 1890s art, both in Finland and in the Nordic countries. The closed eyes, the downward gaze and the mysterious dim lighting are typical of symbolism, popular genre at the time.

The painting shows a young woman, Maija, in the foreground looking down, with a yellowing light hitting her face. Behind her stands Pekka, one hand resting on the back of his wife's chair, looking straight ahead.

text.label: Text
text.value: Maija Halonen was a hardworking and a multi-talented woman, who dreamed of becoming a professional pianist. Although she ended up being a housewife, and responsible for the familyâ€™s money management in Halosenniemi, she got her own Steinway piano and was able to continue enjoying the playing. Moreover, she pursued a remarkable career as a literary translator. After putting her eight children to sleep, she used to start working on translations from Italian, Norwegian, Swedish and German into Finnish. This was also a way to earn some much-needed money for the family.

text.label: Text
text.value: JÃ¤rnefelt has depicted his wife Saimi resting on a flowerbed. The work is painted in a broad brushstroke technique and the large white clouds, blooming daisies and red clovers evoke a serene summer feeling. The work is inspired by Claude Monet's La Prairie (1876).

text.label: Text
text.value: The vast lake landscape around the Koli national park captures the beauty of Finnish nature.

text.label: Text
text.value: Suviranta was completed in 1897. The heart of the villa was Eero JÃ¤rnefeltâ€™s atelier where dances were also often held. However, the garden had also its importance and Eero was very much involved in its upkeep.

text.label: Text
text.value: J. H. Erkko , was a versatile writer who played a significant role in shaping Finnish literature and culture during the late 19th century. He is particularly remembered for his contributions as a poet, journalist, and an educator. For Erkko, language was the instrument of public education and education was the only way to power. He thus worked enthusiastically to improve the status of the Finnish language and pursued a long career as a school teacher.Â  Despite his contributions to Finnish national identity, Erkko's personal life had its challenges. He had his own house, but the dream of having his own family never came true. He died at a young age and got to live in the artist community only five years before his passing.

text.label: Text
text.value: The most famous Finnish composer was a one of the most important writers of symphonies and tone poems of the 20th century and perhaps in musical history as a whole. Raised by mostly female relatives, it was his uncle Per who first introduced him to the world of music. Sibelius' progress in his studies was quick, and at an early stage he was already being described as a musical genius. He had his career on the rise in turn of the 20th century, but his life was overshadowed by the death of his young daughter and the excessive use of alcohol during wild and long nights in Helsinki.

text.label: Text
text.value: Jean Sibelius by Eero JÃ¤rnefelt in 1892

text.label: Text
text.value: It is probably no coincidence that time in Ainola was fruitful for Sibeliusâ€™ career and made him rediscover the joy of composing. The third Symphony, completed in 1907, reflects a new, brighter era. "Despite everything there is nevertheless a lot of the major key in life. The III [Symphony] flows in C major!" He said.

text.label: Text
text.value: Erkkola, designed by Pekka and Antti Halonen, was completed shortly after Halosenniemi, as the residence of the poet J. H. Erkko. As an admirer of Finnish national writer Aleksis Kivi, Erkko wanted to have his villa built as close to the national writerâ€™s memorial cottage as possible. The log house, 300 square meters in size, is an example of National Romantic style and serves today as a home museum.

text.label: Text
text.value: The timber-built villa was designed by the renowned Finnish architect Lars Sonck.

text.label: Text
text.value: Juhani Aho and painter Venny Soldan-Brofeldt were the first residents to settle in the area.Â  As Juhani Aho didnâ€™t want to own anything, the family never owned the villa but always signed a lease for a year ahead. Life in Ahola was considered bohemian yet cozy:Â  Venny had her own atelier in the house which also became a living room for not only the family but also their friends. The studio had a small stage where the artist familiesâ€™ children used to perform their own plays.

text.label: Text
text.value: Venny Soldan-Brofeldt was a talented painter and suffragette who led an international life. Unlike many other women of the time, Venny continued her career even after starting a family. Alongside painting, she illustrated children's books and magazines, made miniature sculptures and mantelpieces and was one of the founders of the â€œArt for Schoolsâ€ association. She was an active feminist who used to startle her neighbors by wearing trousers, cycling and smoking pipe.

text.label: Text
text.value:
Prior to moving to Lake Tuusula, painter Pekka Halonen had often visited the area for combined skiing and painting trips and fallen in love with its scenery. He had already then decided the perfect spot for his own house, and after lengthy negotiations, he managed to buy the land from a local farmer.Â  The villa was designed by Halonen himself and his brother Antti served as the construction manager.

Life in Halosenniemi was rather simple yet hospitable. The most important room in the house was the atelier with a high ceiling: it provided enough space for large artworks, such as altarpieces, and also served as a concert hall. Its good acoustics provided an excellent place for musical performances: Maija's piano was played by Toivo Kuula, Jean Sibelius and other Finnish composers and musicians on many occasions.

text.label: Text
text.value: Jean Sibelius playing the Steinway grand piano in Ainola

text.label: Text
text.value: Ainola (translates as "Aino's place") was located far enough from the hustle and bustle of the capital city and its peaceful surroundings provided inspiration for Sibeliusâ€™ artistic work. During his intensive composition sessions, the rest of the family had to stay quiet without disturbing the master - the daughters were only allowed to practice for their music lessons in the house next doors or when their father went out for a walk .

text.label: Text
text.value:
The Aho family moved back to Helsinki in 1911 to make it easier for Juhani Aho to participate the meetings of
the bible translation committee and
for the boys to attend school. The JÃ¤rnefelt family decided to do the same in 1917, but Suviranta remained as their place for spending the summer and holidays. Others of the artist community lived in the area until the end of their lives.Â

text.label: Text
text.value:
The JÃ¤rnefelt family with composer Jean Sibelius. Standing: Arvid, Armas, Eero and his wife Saimi JÃ¤rnefelt. Seated: Aino Sibelius (nÃ©e JÃ¤rnefelt), Elisabeth JÃ¤rnefelt, Jean Sibelius, Emmy (Arvid's wife) and Eero (Arvid's son), Elli JÃ¤rnefelt (Aino's sister), Mikael Clodt (Elisabeth's brother) and Kasper JÃ¤rnefelt in 1896. 

Both Eero and Saimiâ€™s family members were part of the cultural circles of the time and visited the house often. The family had close ties especially with Ainola residence: the families' children were cousins.

text.label: Text
text.value: The third oldest child of the Swan family started her career as an actress at the Finnish Theatre. Having a strong need for self-expression, Saimi had difficulties in combining  family life with her work. Therefore, she decided to abandon theatre and focus on writing and translating literature. She translated, for example, Charles Dickensâ€™ novel â€œA Tale of Two Citiesâ€ into Finnish.

text.label: Text
text.value: Eero JÃ¤rnefeltÂ  was born into cultural JÃ¤rnelt family that included brothers author Arvid JÃ¤rnefelt, composer Armas JÃ¤rnefelt, and sister Aino JÃ¤rnefelt, the wife of Jean Sibelius. He studied Fine arts in Helsinki, St Petersburg and Paris and was influenced by the Naturalism of Jules Bastien. He was best known for his portraits and landscapes of the area around the Koli National Park.

text.label: Text
text.value: Portrait of Aino Sibelius (1908) painted by his brother Eero JÃ¤rnefelt

text.label: Text
text.value: The sister of Eero JÃ¤rnefelt met Jean Sibelius in 1888. At the time, writer Juhani Aho was also expressing interest towards her, but she refused his proposal for marriage and made a couple with Sibelius instead. Due to his husbandâ€™s demanding work, Aino had to concentrate on looking after the family. In Ainola, she was in charge of the decor and designed pieces of furniture and a sauna building. She was also responsible for the large garden, which fed the family during financially difficult times.

text.label: Text
text.value: Juhani Aho and painter Venny Soldan-Brofeldt moved to the villa rented from the JÃ¤rvenpÃ¤Ã¤ Manor (1). The couple lived in the villa for 14 years and gathered together some of the most important Finnish artists of the time.

text.label: Text
text.value: Suviranta (2), a villa designed by Usko NystrÃ¶m for Eero and Saimi JÃ¤rnefelt, was built on the shore of Lake TuusulanjÃ¤rvi.

text.label: Text
text.value: The atelier home Halosenniemi (3) was built by Pekka and Maija Halonen. Prior to the completion of the artist's home, the Halonen family had lived on the shore of Lake TuusulanjÃ¤rvi since 1898.

text.label: Text
text.value: Erkkola (4), designed by Pekka and Antti Halonen, was completed shortly after Halosenniemi, as the residence of the poet J. H. Erkko.Â

text.label: Text
text.value: The Sibelius family's Ainola (5) was built on KielomÃ¤ki, which had been bought from the JÃ¤rvenpÃ¤Ã¤ Manor. The log house was located opposite Suviranta and also overlooked Ahola.
